name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet: @jbogard I do, but maybe because I work with "enterprise digital transformation" 😂

name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet: @jbogard overall I don't disagree with you on anything, I merely wanted to point out that "full stack" is something I struggle a lot with on many fronts, and I see many facades of it, and I don't think we should trivialize it to "complex JS framework" problem only, that's all

name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet: @jbogard The democratization of cloud, data science & embedded systems has lead to a situation where massively complex solutions appear to be easily implemented. But It has put an unfair pressure on lots of engineers, cause it's often expected that everyone can do everything: it's "easy"

name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet: @jbogard the "lots of fast changing complex JS Frameworks" is just one manifestation of the "full stack" problem, but to me it goes deeper and it touches the root core of what it means to be a software engineer.

name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet:
@jbogard of course not every project needs that, and there is no one size fits all, but from my experience, more and more companies want a) mobile apps b) SPA c) some IoT d) data science. cause it's "easy" these days. 
IMHO that's how you end up with "full stack" craziness

name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet: @jbogard ultimately, no matter how you slice it, the mobile app must be developed and hooked up into the backend, and the sensors must be programmed and connected over BLE and big data part must be handled and so on. And you can only have that many "specialized" folks

name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet: @jbogard it's not a matter of right or wrong, it's a matter of constitutes frontend and backend. even you bundle your HTMLs with your ASP.NETs there is still a whole world out there that needs to be done before a product can ship and that may end up handled by those "full stack" people

name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet: @jbogard "just" delivering a story front to back may span a monumental amount of technologies, paradigms and systems these days

name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet: @jbogard yeah but the scope "front" (web, mobile devices, IoT etc) and what is "back" (messaging, big data, devops, cloud native, PaaS services, data science etc) has changed dramatically

name: Filip W
description: Software engineer with Asperger's. Author, quantum computing nomad, OSS contributor, Microsoft MVP. Works on @omnisharp🦄 @mapleleafs fan 💙
tweet: @jbogard I think the assumption is that full stack used to be HTML+JS+some PHP/MySQL. These days full stack means iOS, Android, heaps of JS libraries, micrososervices in multiple languages, Docker, Kubernetes, ELK stack, Service Bus, DB/storage types and throw in some AI model training
